D1C-C62AA06E6158</gtr:id><gtr:name>Institut Recherche pour le Developpment</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Institut recherche pour le developpment</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>LMTG-UMR 5563</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>14 avenue Edouard Belin</gtr:line3><gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>France</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PROJECT_PARTNER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/89B67BA0-D9B9-44D8-A2FA-580E970CD20D"><gtr:id>89B67BA0-D9B9-44D8-A2FA-580E970CD20D</gtr:id><gtr:name>Michigan State University</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>301 Administration Building</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>East Lansing</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Michigan 48823-1046</gtr:line5><gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>United States</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PROJECT_PARTNER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/8780DEDE-61C4-4050-BBE0-5A9A908B54C8"><gtr:id>8780DEDE-61C4-4050-BBE0-5A9A908B54C8</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Rolf</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Erhart</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Aalto</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/7E4C4900-273B-41E2-A224-76CF012B1827"><gtr:id>7E4C4900-273B-41E2-A224-76CF012B1827</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Andrew</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Nicholas</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/8B497E1E-3975-4A41-83B7-48259B5F6B12"><gtr:id>8B497E1E-3975-4A41-83B7-48259B5F6B12</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Luiz</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Aragao</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=NE%2FH009108%2F1"><gtr:id>D12A2F45-9611-48BE-AD33-A390BC7CF1C8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Do floods matter? Bridging the gap between fluvial morphodynamics and alluvial architecture</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>NE/H009108/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Most lowland rivers flow across large floodplain complexes composed of sediment deposited during floods. These floodplains, and the sedimentary deposits of which they are composed, are of considerable environmental significance. For example, floodplain deposits are regularly used to infer the nature and timing of past climate change, or to assess the impact of upstream landscape disturbance by human activity. Furthermore, the balance between processes of sediment deposition and reworking, due to river migration, determines the residence time of sediment in the floodplain. This is critically important for biogeochemical cycling (eg. of Carbon) and for the transport and fate of sediment associated nutrients and contaminants. Numerical models are important tools that are needed to predict the way that floodplains build up over time and recycle sediment, in order to provide quantitative understanding of floodplain functioning in the context of the diverse environmental applications outlined above. However, despite the need for such models, no model currently exists that is capable of representing the processes involved in the construction and evolution of floodplains over the timescales relevant to these applications (decades to millennia). The reason for this is that realistic models of floodplain evolution need to represent the complex behaviour of the floodwaters that control sediment transport and deposition. However, to do this it is necessary to solve the equations of fluid motion, which is time consuming (in computational terms). For this reason, existing models of floodplain construction neglect these hydraulic and hydrologic controls and, consequently, are unable to predict how floodplains evolve in a way that is physically realistic. This project aims to address this fundamental problem by developing &amp;amp; evaluating a new generation of hydraulically-driven approaches to modelling floodplain construction and evolution. The model developed here will be applicable over periods of up to 100,000 years, yet will have at its core a physically-based hydrodynamic model more usually restricted to applications involving individual floods. This will be achieved by using two approaches to reduce model run times: (1) Parallelising the code for implementation using High Performance Computing; and (2) Developing a series of novel methods of parameterising the effects of fine scale floodplain topography to allow the model to be implemented at reduced grid resolutions, thus substantially increasing model efficiency. The key strength of this modelling approach is that it will allow long-term floodplain evolution to be simulated using an approach underpinned by sound fluid dynamics principles. The model will be evaluated using field and remote sensing data collected from an extensive, natural floodplain system, that is unaffected by either human activity or the effects of Holocene sea level change. Model evaluation will be carried out over the past century and over the Holocene. Following this, the model will be used to conduct a series of numerical experiments designed to investigate the relationships between floodplain evolution, sedimentary deposits and environmental conditions (climate, flood regime, sediment supply, flood basin geometry, &amp;amp; tectonic setting). In combination, field evidence and model simulations will provide new quantitative insight into questions concerning floodplain functioning that have never been addressed due to the current lack of a physically-realistic hydraulically-driven model of long-term floodplain evolution.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2014-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/8A03ED41-E67D-4F4A-B5DD-AAFB272B6471"><gtr:id>8A03ED41-E67D-4F4A-B5DD-AAFB272B6471</gtr:id><gtr:name>NERC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-12-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>485285</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Institute of Development Research (IRD)</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>France, French Republic</gtr:country><gtr:description>Meeting with project partners</gtr:description><gtr:id>ECDC3976-641E-4313-9A60-2A980411A311</gtr:id><gtr:piContribution>Meeting in Toulouse with project partners IRD (Institut de recherche pour le d&amp;eacute;veloppement) to discuss project and collaboration</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2011-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Three periods of field work were carried out on the Rio Beni in Bolivia. This work involved river water level and bank top surveys, floodplain coring to measure rates of sediment deposition during floods, vegetation and global positioning system surveys of the floodplain topography. Field data collection was combined with GIS analysis of river migration over a c. 50 year period, with analysis of existing remote sensing datasets quantifying floodplain topography (SRTM) and with numerical modelling of flow, sediment transport and river evolution. Key findings from this work include:

1) The model developed here explained how factors such as sediment type and vegetation can control the morphology (shape) of large sand-bed rivers like the Rio Beni.

2) The models and field data provide new understanding of the interactions between river processes and landforms, and sedimentary deposits.

3) This work illustrated the key role played by heterogeneity in floodplain deposits as a control on rates and styles of river migration.

4) Our results show how factors such as sediment supply to rivers and river migration can influence the frequency of lowland flooding, and illustrate that year to year variability in flooding can be driven by many non-climatic factors.

5) These results have important implications for the interpretation of sedimentary deposits as archives of past flooding.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The models developed in the project have the potential to be used to predict river responses to environmental change, or to quantify the controls on alluvial architecture (of interest to the hydrocarbon industry, for example).</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>7ED86DE6-9045-438A-8625-17FFD2B49D2E</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/4244013E-3A9E-45D9-BFFF-DB04F6CCE4AF"><gtr:id>4244013E-3A9E-45D9-BFFF-DB04F6CCE4AF</gtr:id><gtr:title>Morphodynamic diversity of the world's largest rivers</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Geology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/21ca196aa8a0d6cffded40f47fe71a5c"><gtr:id>21ca196aa8a0d6cffded40f47fe71a5c</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Nicholas A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/7E3308D3-BECD-4765-AD80-3989D03C6D46"><gtr:id>7E3308D3-BECD-4765-AD80-3989D03C6D46</gtr:id><gtr:title>Interaction between meander dynamics and floodplain heterogeneity in a large tropical sand-bed river: the Rio Beni, Bolivian Amazon</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Earth Surface Processes and Landforms</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/20bbd92ac6f75f04edc2c4fc999db822"><gtr:id>20bbd92ac6f75f04edc2c4fc999db822</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Schwendel A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date></gtr